tcsh: guard xcatgets() against a failed catalog descriptor (musl)

POSIX requires catgets() to return the supplied default string `s` when
called with an invalid catalog descriptor.  glibc and the BSDs honour this;
musl's catgets() does NOT -- it dereferences (const char *)catd unconditionally
(reading catd+4, i.e. address 0x3 when catd == (nl_catd)-1), so it segfaults.

tcsh always calls xcatgets()/CGETS() with whatever catopen() returned, and in a
single self-contained static binary there are no `tcsh.cat` files on disk, so
catopen() returns -1 at startup (nlsinit -> iconv_open(nl_langinfo(CODESET),
xcatgets(catd,255,1,"UTF-8"))) and the shell dies before it prints anything.

xcatgets() is the single chokepoint for every catalog lookup (iconv_catgets()
and the CGETS() macro both route through it), so guarding it here makes the
shell robust on musl while leaving real localization intact wherever the
platform's catgets() is conformant and a valid catalog was opened.

--- a/sh.func.c
+++ b/sh.func.c
@@ -2585,6 +2585,16 @@
 {
     char *res;

+    /*
+     * POSIX: catgets() with an invalid catalog descriptor returns the default
+     * string `s`.  musl omits that check and dereferences (char *)-1, so a
+     * static-musl build segfaults the moment catopen() fails -- which it does
+     * in a single binary with no .cat files on disk.  Bail to the built-in
+     * (English) default before touching catgets().
+     */
+    if (ctd == (nl_catd)-1)
+	return (char *)(intptr_t)s;
+
     errno = 0;
     while ((res = catgets(ctd, set_id, msg_id, s)) == s && errno == EINTR) {
 	handle_pending_signals();
